Introudction

For my survey, I decided to focus on sports. I wanted to find out about the learning practices people have around sports and their reasons for learning a new sport.

When designing my form, I made sure to follow guideline 4. For short answer questions, such as “How many sports are you proficient in?”, I ensured that only numbers could be entered, and set a range between 0-100. I included 0 because there is a chance that the respondent may not play any sports proficiently.

The Google Sheet data collected will not be tidy because the data collected from the check boxes are grouped into one cell where the selected options are separated by a comma. This means that the data is not tidy due to the selected options not having a column (or cell) of their own.

Learning reflection

I learned a lot of things from module 2, but the four guidelines were the most memorable. Guideline 1 was especially memorable, as originally, I was just thinking of creating a form with questions and distributing the form to gather responses. However, Guideline 1 taught me that each form must have a clear introduction that explains the purpose of data collection and what the data is being used for. Guideline 3 also taught me to consider my respondents before writing my questions. As the majority of people conducting my survey will be university students, I made sure to include options/questions that were suited to my respondents. My project demonstrates creativity in the form of my survey. I made my form green, added colour to it, and attached an image as the header. This was not necessary for Project 2, but I wanted to make my form more aesthetically pleasing and to suit the theme of my questions. I also added CSS, covered in module 1 and stuck with the colour green as this colour often represents sports which was the theme of my survey. I am curious about the data tidying aspect of data technologies. I think that creating surveys is generally straightforward and not that difficult. However, I would like to explore how companies tidy their data after large surveys. For surveys that contain many questions and a variety of answers, it would be difficult to manipulate the data to create graphs or tables to analyse or develop conclusions from the data. I also believe knowing how to manipulate data is a useful skill to have.
